SIMPLE: hunt
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hunt
<hw>Hunt</hw> <pr>(h⟦ucr⟧nt)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Hunted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hunting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>huntian</ets> to hunt;
cf. <ets>hentan</ets> to follow, pursue, Goth. <ets>hin<?/an</ets> (in
comp.) to seize. ⟦root⟧36. Cf. <er>Hent</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
search for or follow after, as game or wild animals; to chase; to pursue
for the purpose of catching or killing; to follow with dogs or guns for
sport or exercise; <as>as, to <ex>hunt</ex> a deer</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like a dog, he <qex>hunts</qex> in dreams.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To search diligently after; to seek; to pursue; to
follow; -- often with <xex>out</xex> or <xex>up</xex>; <as>as, to
<ex>hunt</ex> up the facts; to <ex>hunt</ex> out
evidence.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Evil shall <qex>hunt</qex> the violent man to overthrow him.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. cxl. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To drive; to chase; -- with <xex>down</xex>,
<xex>from</xex>, <xex>away</xex>, etc.; <as>as, to <ex>hunt</ex> down a
criminal; he was <ex>hunted</ex> from the parish.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To use or manage in the chase, as hounds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>hunts</qex> a pack of dogs.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To use or traverse in pursuit of game; <as>as, he
<ex>hunts</ex> the woods, or the country</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Change Ringing)</fld> <def>To move or shift the
order of (a bell) in a regular course of changes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hunt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hunt
<hw>Hunt</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To follow the chase; to
go out in pursuit of game; to course with hounds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Esau went to the field to <qex>hunt</qex> for venison.</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. xxvii. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To seek; to pursue; to search; -- with
<xex>for</xex> or <xex>after</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He after honor <qex>hunts</qex>, I after love.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>To be in a state of instability
of movement or forced oscillation, as a governor which has a large
movement of the balls for small change of load, an arc-lamp clutch
mechanism which moves rapidly up and down with variations of current, or
the like; also, to seesaw, as a pair of alternators working in
parallel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Change Ringing)</fld> <def>To shift up and down in
order regularly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To hunt counter</b></col>, <cd>to trace the scent
backward in hunting, as a hound to go back on one's steps.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hunt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hunt
<hw>Hunt</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or practice of
chasing wild animals; chase; pursuit; search.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>hunt</qex> is up; the morn is bright and gray.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The game secured in the hunt.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A pack of hounds.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An association of huntsmen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A district of country hunted over.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every landowner within the <qex>hunt</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>London
Field.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hunt-counter</ent>⟦br⟧
